am of study in the early Academy and with the architecture of the Parthenon. Lehman and Weinman argue that the Parthenon can be seen as the foremost embodiment of the practical working through of mathematical knowledge in its time, serving as a mediator between the early reception of Ancient Near-Eastern mathematical ideas and their integration into Greek thought as a form of liberal education, as the latter came to be defined by Plato and his followers. With its Doric architecture characterized by symmetria (commensurability) and harmonia (harmony; joining together), concepts explored contemporaneously by Philolaus, the Parthenon engages dialectical thought in ways that are of enduring relevance for the project of liberal education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMathematicsxHistory. 0aPhilosophy, Ancient. 4aEducation : Education. 4aHistory : Architectural History/Architecture. 4aPhilosophy : Ancient Greek Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aScience, Mathematics, and Technology : Mathematics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aLehman, Geoff, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeinman, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWeinman, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2018z978311149142440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846843340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438468433423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438468433/original  a978-3-11-149142-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles